WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:13.160
Thank you for coming everybody and I'm super excited and delighted to be talking to you

00:00:13.160 --> 00:00:19.520
today and leading off the Shiny track about effective use of Shiny modules in your Shiny

00:00:19.520 --> 00:00:21.320
application development.

00:00:21.320 --> 00:00:26.400
You can follow along with the slides at bit.ly slash modules 2019, I have a few links in

00:00:26.400 --> 00:00:30.520
there if you'd like to click those as I go along.

00:00:30.520 --> 00:00:33.200
I'll lead off with a little bit about my journey with Shiny.

00:00:33.200 --> 00:00:37.759
I was one of the early adopters when it was first released to CRAN and like Flynn here

00:00:37.759 --> 00:00:42.680
looking at the master control program, I was absolutely hooked.

00:00:42.680 --> 00:00:48.200
Like a lot of you in the room, I started making small prototypes to showcase not only to myself

00:00:48.200 --> 00:00:54.480
but to my collaborators or colleagues what Shiny was capable of and learning through

00:00:54.480 --> 00:00:56.759
examples along the way.

00:00:56.759 --> 00:01:02.119
I had the good fortune of attending the Shiny DevCon a few years ago and I have begun my

00:01:02.119 --> 00:01:09.339
journey to slowly ascend Joe Ching's ladder of enlightenment and fast forwarding to today,

00:01:09.339 --> 00:01:15.680
I am now a developer of pretty large and complex applications that often integrate multiple

00:01:15.680 --> 00:01:16.680
systems.

00:01:16.680 --> 00:01:23.080
So let me dive into my first attempt at one of these types of applications.

00:01:23.080 --> 00:01:28.199
What I wanted to do with this application is empower our statisticians at our company

00:01:28.199 --> 00:01:34.199
that didn't have any experience of our programming to be able to use a very sophisticated algorithm

00:01:34.199 --> 00:01:40.199
called subgroup identification with a package that we have open sourced on CRAN called TSDT.

00:01:40.199 --> 00:01:44.320
We don't have time to dive into the details of this package but the key point is that

00:01:44.320 --> 00:01:50.959
this application had very non-trivial requirements of having persistent session management, a

00:01:50.959 --> 00:01:55.559
dynamic UI based on the data that was loaded by the user, and being able to integrate with

00:01:55.559 --> 00:01:57.500
our HPC cluster.

00:01:57.500 --> 00:02:00.599
So I encountered quite a few challenges along the way.

00:02:00.599 --> 00:02:06.080
I duplicated pretty similar UI widgets throughout the app, I did not organize the code well

00:02:06.080 --> 00:02:12.320
at all because I never built anything this large in R in my entire life before this point,

00:02:12.320 --> 00:02:16.600
and extending the features when statisticians would say, hey, can you do this, can you do

00:02:16.600 --> 00:02:19.639
this, ended up being very challenging as a result.

00:02:19.639 --> 00:02:24.979
So I want to show you next kind of a schematic of what these components looked like and how

00:02:24.979 --> 00:02:27.020
they related to each other.

00:02:27.020 --> 00:02:29.119
You notice all this mess of arrows, right?

00:02:29.119 --> 00:02:34.399
I have all these relationships of inputs for one module going out, outputs of another module,

00:02:34.399 --> 00:02:39.119
not even module yet, these subcomponents, but it looks very messy.

00:02:39.119 --> 00:02:44.679
I've even duplicated these similar widgets like variable selections or visualization,

00:02:44.720 --> 00:02:50.000
and frankly it gives me flashbacks to a very good analogy put out by Ian Little of this

00:02:50.000 --> 00:02:52.520
is just a reactive spaghetti mess.

00:02:52.520 --> 00:02:55.240
And so how can we get out of this?

00:02:55.240 --> 00:03:01.279
What in the Shiny ecosystem can help us solve a lot of these issues of managing this complex

00:03:01.279 --> 00:03:02.279
application?

00:03:02.279 --> 00:03:07.520
Well, since you're here, you're probably not surprised, it's modules to the rescue.

00:03:07.520 --> 00:03:12.080
This is going to unlock a lot of possibilities, but it's not just unlocking that door, it's

00:03:12.080 --> 00:03:14.600
what do we do afterwards?

00:03:14.600 --> 00:03:18.119
So to orient ourselves, let's talk about what exactly modules are.

00:03:18.119 --> 00:03:22.399
There's quite a few ways of defining this, but the simplest way is that it's a way for

00:03:22.399 --> 00:03:28.600
us to compose complex applications of smaller and more understandable pieces.

00:03:28.600 --> 00:03:30.679
Along the ride comes quite a few benefits.

00:03:30.679 --> 00:03:35.399
We are able to avoid namespace collisions when we duplicate these similar user interface

00:03:35.399 --> 00:03:36.399
widgets.

00:03:36.399 --> 00:03:42.360
It allows us to encapsulate or compartmentalize these distinct components of our application,

00:03:42.360 --> 00:03:47.679
which in turn helps us organize the code base much better into easier to understand

00:03:47.679 --> 00:03:54.839
pieces and that also is going to lead to facilitating effective team development and if you then

00:03:54.839 --> 00:04:00.119
check out Colin Faye's poster on advanced Shiny development, he also emphasized that

00:04:00.119 --> 00:04:02.520
same principle.

00:04:02.520 --> 00:04:04.800
Now take a step back for a second.

00:04:04.800 --> 00:04:11.320
I think this sounds quite familiar if you're familiar with R because R functions themselves

00:04:11.320 --> 00:04:17.000
are a very important way to avoid collisions and save variable names with just general

00:04:17.000 --> 00:04:23.880
R code and they are essential when you go from simple, quick, dirty data analysis pipelines

00:04:23.880 --> 00:04:30.679
to a more sophisticated and extensive workflow like a lot of the packages that you see today.

00:04:30.679 --> 00:04:36.399
So let's imagine that I'd had modules available when I was making that first complex application,

00:04:36.399 --> 00:04:39.760
which was admittedly well before modules came around.

00:04:39.760 --> 00:04:44.000
This is what it could look like if I could go back in time and bring present me back

00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:48.200
to then and architect this in a much more logical way.

00:04:48.200 --> 00:04:51.559
You see these four boxes here?

00:04:51.559 --> 00:04:55.839
These kind of mimic the workflow of the user to visit this application.

00:04:55.839 --> 00:05:01.880
They're creating a welcome interface, they import data, they run the analyses on HPC

00:05:01.880 --> 00:05:04.160
and then they interrogate the results.

00:05:04.160 --> 00:05:08.760
But this doesn't look like the spaghetti mess anymore because I'm able to define very clearly

00:05:08.760 --> 00:05:16.279
within these big boxes these sub-module relationships and also I'm not copying pasting little sub-modules

00:05:16.279 --> 00:05:23.160
in each of these areas, I'm able to encapsulate them in the namespace of these bigger modules.

00:05:23.160 --> 00:05:28.600
So I have to be honest with you, I did not arrive at this mindset right away, not even

00:05:28.600 --> 00:05:29.600
close.

00:05:29.600 --> 00:05:35.040
It has taken me a lot of practice and trial and error to get to this kind of mindset.

00:05:35.040 --> 00:05:41.679
So you can think of it as we're on this highway to, in essence, the mastery of modules.

00:05:41.679 --> 00:05:47.119
This is an ambitious goal, but I imagine if you're at least peripherally familiar of modules,

00:05:47.119 --> 00:05:51.480
you've probably been on this first stop along this highway of being able to create and use

00:05:51.480 --> 00:05:55.799
fairly simple modules occasionally throughout your app.

00:05:55.799 --> 00:06:01.839
Now I would challenge that I don't think many people in the room are at these points yet.

00:06:01.839 --> 00:06:07.600
Do you have a good handle on how you structure the communications with modules and even more

00:06:07.600 --> 00:06:12.440
advanced than that, communications between modules that are perhaps siblings of others?

00:06:12.440 --> 00:06:16.959
We don't have time to cover all of this today, but I'm going to show you a few concepts to

00:06:16.959 --> 00:06:23.760
get you on your way that highway to those later points near that very pretty sunset.

00:06:23.760 --> 00:06:29.760
But all of this traveling and this road to mastery modules leads to these very important

00:06:29.760 --> 00:06:31.480
principles.

00:06:31.480 --> 00:06:33.679
First of which is careful design.

00:06:33.679 --> 00:06:38.760
Think about these things as you're developing a module, such as what does it do?

00:06:38.760 --> 00:06:40.880
What is it trying to accomplish?

00:06:40.880 --> 00:06:43.000
And also, what should I call this thing?

00:06:43.000 --> 00:06:45.359
Now you may be wondering, why would I throw that in there?

00:06:45.359 --> 00:06:50.359
Well, if you can't name your module easily, that's a pretty big warning sign that it's

00:06:50.359 --> 00:06:52.679
probably trying to do too much.

00:06:52.679 --> 00:06:59.200
So you want to keep it fairly simple, yet accomplishing a very powerful goal.

00:06:59.200 --> 00:07:03.640
The other key principle is thinking about your inputs and return values.

00:07:03.640 --> 00:07:04.959
What kind of inputs are you going to have?

00:07:04.959 --> 00:07:08.920
Are they going to be static type inputs or reactive inputs?

00:07:08.920 --> 00:07:14.200
How complex do you want to make these return values and which of these outputs are serving

00:07:14.200 --> 00:07:18.940
as inputs to the other modules, this kind of communication principle.

00:07:18.940 --> 00:07:23.600
If you take away nothing else from this talk, take away this.

00:07:23.600 --> 00:07:27.839
Modules that are built without these principles is quite simply not enough.

00:07:28.279 --> 00:07:33.760
I'm going to illustrate how we can at least use these principles effectively in practice.

00:07:33.760 --> 00:07:40.440
So I'm going to transition to, admittedly, a little demo here of an application that

00:07:40.440 --> 00:07:46.000
we have deployed on the Shiny Gallery, and I call it the Ames Housing Data Explorer.

00:07:46.000 --> 00:07:51.959
It is using the Ames housing data set, which is available on CRAN, and it lets the user

00:07:51.959 --> 00:07:56.839
select these points with the plot brushing after they choose variables, and then it shows

00:07:56.839 --> 00:08:02.440
up these points metadata under word, and then they can click that checkbox and highlight

00:08:02.440 --> 00:08:05.399
those points with the sales price.

00:08:05.399 --> 00:08:08.279
So you can play with that on the Shiny Gallery.

00:08:08.279 --> 00:08:13.640
I'll have links to that right here in the slides if you want to play with that.

00:08:13.640 --> 00:08:17.200
But now let's look at how this is kind of organized in a sense, just looking at the

00:08:17.200 --> 00:08:18.600
picture of this.

00:08:18.600 --> 00:08:22.320
We have these sections for the user selects variables.

00:08:22.320 --> 00:08:27.279
We have the section where, of course, the variables are being plotted in a scatter plot,

00:08:27.279 --> 00:08:33.440
and then we have that data table below that's summarizing the metadata of these results.

00:08:33.440 --> 00:08:35.919
Well really, these are all modules here.

00:08:35.919 --> 00:08:41.119
We have a variable module, we have a visualization module, and we have that data table module

00:08:41.119 --> 00:08:42.119
below.

00:08:42.119 --> 00:08:45.559
That shouldn't have been there.

00:08:45.559 --> 00:08:51.719
So let's talk about some techniques that help get you into this road to mastering modules

00:08:51.719 --> 00:08:53.200
more effectively.

00:08:53.200 --> 00:08:58.400
This first tangible item you can do is, of course, documenting your modules.

00:08:58.400 --> 00:09:04.280
Now here, if you see on the top here, I've highlighted, of course, the input parameters.

00:09:04.280 --> 00:09:09.479
They're not remarkable here because this is a very simple module, but notice I am taking

00:09:09.479 --> 00:09:10.960
the act of documenting.

00:09:10.960 --> 00:09:13.200
It doesn't have to be Roxygen2.

00:09:13.200 --> 00:09:17.520
It could be any system you like, but this is going to help you later on when you start

00:09:17.520 --> 00:09:19.080
to use these in practice.

00:09:19.080 --> 00:09:21.359
I don't know why that is going away.

00:09:21.359 --> 00:09:29.280
I'm going to kill that right now.

00:09:29.280 --> 00:09:32.760
So then look at the return object of this as well.

00:09:32.760 --> 00:09:36.080
I've actually been intentional about naming these components.

00:09:36.080 --> 00:09:37.080
Okay.

00:09:37.080 --> 00:09:38.559
VLC, you're going bye-bye.

00:09:38.559 --> 00:09:44.559
Let's do that real quick.

00:09:44.559 --> 00:09:45.559
Okay.

00:09:45.559 --> 00:09:47.880
We're back to business.

00:09:47.880 --> 00:09:52.400
So let's look at the return module or the return object here.

00:09:52.400 --> 00:09:58.799
We have a name list, in this case, X bar and Y bar, which are simply inputs that were taken

00:09:58.799 --> 00:10:00.280
from the UI.

00:10:00.280 --> 00:10:05.239
I'm actually being intentional here because this is an example of you're constructing

00:10:05.239 --> 00:10:09.039
this name list to articulate the intent of this module.

00:10:09.039 --> 00:10:13.719
You might think of it as like an accessor type module, but these end up being quite

00:10:13.719 --> 00:10:19.280
important as you think about making these modules simple, yet can be quite powerful.

00:10:19.280 --> 00:10:24.640
I'm going to take a little detour here to talk about more of a development topic of

00:10:24.640 --> 00:10:29.599
modules, a section that really even trips me up to this day sometimes.

00:10:29.599 --> 00:10:33.960
In this example, we have this little plot one var reactive, and we're just simply assigning

00:10:33.960 --> 00:10:36.039
that from an input.

00:10:36.039 --> 00:10:41.479
And then this mod module, when we call that, we're supplying that plot one var as one of

00:10:41.479 --> 00:10:42.880
the arguments.

00:10:43.039 --> 00:10:47.359
And within that module server-side processing, we have a reactive not doing anything special

00:10:47.359 --> 00:10:48.359
here.

00:10:48.359 --> 00:10:51.020
It's just simply referencing that plot one var.

00:10:51.020 --> 00:10:56.479
So keep this in your mind a little bit as we talk about when do we put parentheses after

00:10:56.479 --> 00:10:59.400
these names and when don't we?

00:10:59.400 --> 00:11:03.840
So I believe a lot of you are familiar with, of course, the tidyverse and things like the

00:11:03.840 --> 00:11:08.679
per package and base RL apply.

00:11:08.679 --> 00:11:15.559
For those uninitiated, the map function takes this vector of stuff and applies the function

00:11:15.559 --> 00:11:17.880
F to each of these pieces.

00:11:17.880 --> 00:11:22.559
Notice that in the map call, we're taking the name of that function as the input, but

00:11:22.559 --> 00:11:26.359
then we're invoking that function on these pieces individually.

00:11:26.359 --> 00:11:31.520
You may be asking yourself, how in the world does this apply to modules and Shiny in general?

00:11:31.520 --> 00:11:35.960
Well, it's going back to this little pseudocode example.

00:11:35.960 --> 00:11:41.760
Notice that this call module directive, in essence, is similar to that map function where

00:11:41.760 --> 00:11:46.520
we're passing in the name of that reactive without the parentheses.

00:11:46.520 --> 00:11:51.320
But then when we go inside that module, we're doing what we do in typical Shiny when we

00:11:51.320 --> 00:11:52.919
deal with a reactive.

00:11:52.919 --> 00:11:55.940
We're referencing that with the parentheses inside.

00:11:55.940 --> 00:11:59.659
But then when we have that foo reactive, we want to take that back out.

00:11:59.659 --> 00:12:01.679
We're now using that name again.

00:12:01.679 --> 00:12:05.640
Now this is admittedly something that you almost have to practice a few times.

00:12:05.640 --> 00:12:09.559
And even to this day, there are some times I get a little mixed up here and there.

00:12:09.559 --> 00:12:13.760
But I'm just sharing some of the lessons I've learned that if you think about these simple

00:12:13.760 --> 00:12:19.719
examples, you can kind of apply them to more complicated workflows.

00:12:19.719 --> 00:12:24.400
Another step that we talked about back in the principles slide is, how do we know whether

00:12:24.400 --> 00:12:27.840
to use static or reactive inputs to these modules?

00:12:27.840 --> 00:12:31.640
So in this code here, I have this scatterplot server module.

00:12:31.640 --> 00:12:36.080
And in those in the documentation, I'm saying that data set parameter is a data frame that's

00:12:36.080 --> 00:12:37.940
non-reactive.

00:12:37.940 --> 00:12:45.039
And then within this plot one object reactive, I'm using that data set name without parentheses.

00:12:45.039 --> 00:12:46.599
Now why is that?

00:12:46.599 --> 00:12:52.119
It's because this data set, if you look at the code from that example app, is simply

00:12:52.119 --> 00:12:55.760
the grab of the AIMS housing data from that package.

00:12:55.760 --> 00:12:57.739
And it's not changing in the app.

00:12:57.739 --> 00:13:02.840
It's literally just serving itself as a source for where all my filtering from that plot

00:13:02.840 --> 00:13:04.840
brushing is going to occur.

00:13:04.840 --> 00:13:09.700
So in this case, we only need that present value because in essence, it's not changing.

00:13:09.700 --> 00:13:12.140
But let's now look at some of those additional parameters.

00:13:12.140 --> 00:13:15.700
In this case, plot one var and plot two vars.

00:13:15.700 --> 00:13:21.000
And if you recall from the previous slides ago, I was forming that as a named list of

00:13:21.000 --> 00:13:23.539
two components of xvar and yvar.

00:13:23.539 --> 00:13:26.739
And notice here, I am using the parentheses this time.

00:13:26.739 --> 00:13:31.739
This is because we don't care just about what the user selected initially, but it's

00:13:31.739 --> 00:13:34.460
also what they will select in the future.

00:13:34.460 --> 00:13:40.580
And just like with Shiny itself, when we want to invoke these reactives, we want to be both

00:13:40.580 --> 00:13:43.260
present and future state in mind.

00:13:43.260 --> 00:13:47.419
One little nugget that can trip people up too is when you have this named list that

00:13:47.419 --> 00:13:51.099
you're returning from a module, where do you put those parentheses?

00:13:51.099 --> 00:13:57.580
So in this case, you put it after that xvar or yvar reference, not after that list name

00:13:57.580 --> 00:13:58.580
itself.

00:13:58.580 --> 00:14:03.179
I've spent quite a few more hours than I care to admit of debugging modules, and if I just

00:14:03.179 --> 00:14:05.099
made that fix, it would have been all done.

00:14:05.099 --> 00:14:08.979
So hopefully I can save you some time as you develop modules.

00:14:08.979 --> 00:14:11.460
Next, it's not just about what you should do.

00:14:11.460 --> 00:14:15.099
I'm going to tell you about a technique that you definitely do not want to do.

00:14:15.099 --> 00:14:18.940
I somewhat affectionately call this the kitchen sink approach.

00:14:18.940 --> 00:14:25.179
So let's imagine you have this reactive values object called rdata, and this is a place where

00:14:25.179 --> 00:14:29.940
in essence in each of these modules I have in this application, instead of following

00:14:29.940 --> 00:14:34.979
that advice I just gave you, imagine I just want to have these reactives here and there,

00:14:34.979 --> 00:14:39.859
and when I need to, I just toss some stuff into that reactive values object.

00:14:39.859 --> 00:14:42.659
Who cares about returning anything out of it?

00:14:42.659 --> 00:14:48.780
Because the best part is when I do the module calls, I just have that one argument retaining

00:14:48.780 --> 00:14:51.780
to that name rdata, that reactive values slot.

00:14:51.780 --> 00:14:55.059
Boy, it seems all rosy unicorns, right?

00:14:55.059 --> 00:14:56.059
Well guess what?

00:14:56.059 --> 00:15:02.599
This is a bad idea, because you've now ventured into the dangerous world of hidden state.

00:15:02.599 --> 00:15:07.580
This is where it's difficult to figure out what is happening to these individual objects

00:15:07.580 --> 00:15:12.580
in the rdata kitchen sink, I would call it, and only certain objects from this are needed

00:15:12.580 --> 00:15:18.460
as you pass from one module to another, and even more importantly, it's losing that contract

00:15:18.460 --> 00:15:21.340
that you've established with these modules.

00:15:21.340 --> 00:15:26.979
So this is a really bad idea, and even in typical R programming, you wouldn't see people

00:15:26.979 --> 00:15:31.780
passing around environments back and forth either, that just is ugly stuff, so don't

00:15:31.780 --> 00:15:33.460
do it.

00:15:33.460 --> 00:15:38.700
So we've talked about a few things, what does this actually mean to you as a Shiny developer?

00:15:38.700 --> 00:15:43.299
Well I think you may already know, because R as I mentioned is well suited for interactive

00:15:43.299 --> 00:15:49.099
workflows, especially in data science, but then as you go from trivial stuff to non-trivial

00:15:49.099 --> 00:15:54.820
workflows, functions are that essential building block to move from these different types of

00:15:54.820 --> 00:16:01.179
workflows, and defining clear function inputs is essential for effective structure.

00:16:01.179 --> 00:16:05.979
This is no different when you create Shiny apps, especially with modules in mind, because

00:16:05.979 --> 00:16:12.359
using modules with the principles we've discussed is an important piece to bring software engineering

00:16:12.359 --> 00:16:17.119
best practices to your development, such as determining the purpose of the module and

00:16:17.119 --> 00:16:20.039
much of those questions that we asked initially.

00:16:20.039 --> 00:16:21.320
So what's in it for you?

00:16:21.320 --> 00:16:26.159
Again, recapping some of the benefits of modules, you're avoiding namespace collisions for those

00:16:26.159 --> 00:16:31.080
widgets, you're organizing the application into these distinct components, so you can

00:16:31.080 --> 00:16:37.119
facilitate collaboration and more productive development, tracking down bugs, and you're

00:16:37.119 --> 00:16:42.919
using best practices that you learned from your other R development skills and translates

00:16:42.919 --> 00:16:45.520
very well with modules.

00:16:45.520 --> 00:16:50.440
So we have some calls to action, definitely read the new article that we have on the Shiny

00:16:50.440 --> 00:16:55.760
article site for module communication best practices, and keep your eye out for more

00:16:55.760 --> 00:16:58.559
articles in the future in this space.

00:16:58.559 --> 00:17:02.520
Definitely review the example application I've shared on the Shiny gallery for the AIMS

00:17:02.520 --> 00:17:07.239
housing dataset, but I want to mention that this is going to be difficult to get right

00:17:07.239 --> 00:17:14.439
the first time, but just persevere, keep nudging, keep reaching, eventually you will get there.

00:17:14.439 --> 00:17:18.479
But it's taken me a while, but hopefully if you think of these principles in mind it won't

00:17:18.479 --> 00:17:20.719
take you as long as me.

00:17:20.719 --> 00:17:25.520
So that concludes my talk, this is where you can find me in the R community, you may hear

00:17:25.520 --> 00:17:30.400
my voice on a little thing called the R podcast, and I also try to be involved with things

00:17:30.400 --> 00:17:40.280
like R Weekly and Rbind and other efforts, so thank you.

00:17:40.280 --> 00:17:41.280
Thank you.

00:17:41.280 --> 00:17:47.239
We have approximately four minutes, so if there are any questions, I forgot to throw

00:17:47.239 --> 00:17:56.359
the throwable mic, let me go get that, and then you can ask them.

00:17:56.359 --> 00:17:59.800
Thank you.

00:17:59.800 --> 00:18:24.160
Winston has the throwable mic, so if you have questions, look to him.

00:18:24.160 --> 00:18:30.280
Have you been able to integrate modules inside packages for easy distribution of those modules?

00:18:30.280 --> 00:18:34.000
So I personally have not done it yet, but I've certainly seen examples in the community

00:18:34.000 --> 00:18:36.800
where modules have been part of packages.

00:18:36.800 --> 00:18:39.920
So there would be some good examples to follow on there.

00:18:39.920 --> 00:18:44.760
For my use case, I've been preparing for that state, but because of our infrastructure I

00:18:44.760 --> 00:18:50.800
can't deploy an application as a package yet, so that's part of it, but we also have situations

00:18:50.800 --> 00:18:55.760
where these modules are kind of being used in my apps only, but I still use modules to

00:18:55.760 --> 00:19:00.439
help, like the ideas I mentioned, keep them better organized and make sure that I can

00:19:00.439 --> 00:19:05.119
debug them easier and have multiple teammates develop them concurrently, but it's certainly

00:19:05.119 --> 00:19:06.119
possible.

00:19:06.119 --> 00:19:13.359
That was a great talk.

00:19:13.359 --> 00:19:18.000
This is off topic completely, but I loved the R podcast, but it was quiet for a while,

00:19:18.000 --> 00:19:19.000
so I stopped listening.

00:19:19.000 --> 00:19:20.880
Will you be back online with episodes?

00:19:20.880 --> 00:19:25.839
There will be multiple coming from this conference, and I have ideas in mind to keep that sustainable,

00:19:25.839 --> 00:19:31.880
but I thank you for those kind words, thank you.

00:19:31.880 --> 00:19:36.199
Hey, great talk.

00:19:36.199 --> 00:19:42.719
Meme game is strong today, much appreciated about that, but my question goes to along

00:19:42.719 --> 00:19:48.839
the lines of when you create these modules, is there a general rule of thumb for how often

00:19:48.839 --> 00:19:53.420
you're adding new functions into these things, or do they become like giant repositories

00:19:53.420 --> 00:19:59.959
of import functions or modifications for a particular package, or not package, you know

00:19:59.959 --> 00:20:00.959
what I mean?

00:20:00.959 --> 00:20:02.760
Yeah, yeah, I get your point.

00:20:02.760 --> 00:20:05.760
So I think it depends on how you're structuring them.

00:20:05.760 --> 00:20:10.239
One advanced topic that I didn't really get to is that in my applications I often have

00:20:10.239 --> 00:20:15.079
these larger modules that are actually composed of smaller modules inside.

00:20:15.079 --> 00:20:19.680
So the idea is, I think of it as like what is the workflow of the user in your application,

00:20:19.680 --> 00:20:24.959
and if you can organize your app into components, whether it's like tabs in a UI or things like

00:20:24.959 --> 00:20:28.880
that, those are great candidates to have kind of like a wrapper module, and you have these

00:20:28.880 --> 00:20:34.640
more utility modules inside that you can reuse in different parts of your app, but I do admit

00:20:34.640 --> 00:20:39.859
I do have some modules that have quite a bit of functions inside, but I separate those

00:20:39.859 --> 00:20:43.839
out into their own script, and then I can debug them effectively just as if it was like

00:20:43.839 --> 00:20:45.520
an R package in that case.

00:20:45.520 --> 00:20:47.880
It takes a lot of practice though, I do admit that.

